  <section id="healthcare-system">
    <h2>Healthcare System Overview</h2>
    <p>
      Understanding Belize's healthcare limitations is essential for realistic retirement planning. The country has no large hospitals, limited specialist availability, and many conditions require travel abroad for treatment. This isn't a criticism—it's simply the reality of a small country with 400,000 people.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Karl Heusner Memorial Hospital</strong> in Belize City is the country's only public referral hospital. It handles emergencies and has basic surgical capabilities, but equipment is dated and specialist availability is limited. Expats generally use this only for emergencies before evacuation.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Private clinics</strong> in Belize City, San Pedro, and San Ignacio provide routine care: general consultations, basic lab work, minor procedures. Doctors are often trained abroad and provide competent care for everyday health needs. Consultations typically cost $50-80.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>What's not available in Belize:</strong> Complex cardiac care, oncology treatment, advanced imaging (no MRI machines), neurosurgery, and most specialized procedures. For these, you'll need to travel to Chetumal or Cancun (Mexico), Guatemala City, or the United States.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Medical evacuation realities:</strong> From Ambergris Caye, evacuation typically involves small aircraft to Belize City, then air ambulance to Cancun (1 hour) or Miami (2 hours). From mainland locations, ground ambulance to the border followed by care in Chetumal may be fastest for some conditions. Your insurer coordinates this, but understanding the logistics helps with realistic expectations.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Prescription medications:</strong> Basic medications are available at local pharmacies. Specialized medications may need to be imported from Mexico or brought from the US. If you take specific medications, verify availability or plan for a 90-day supply from home.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="costs">
    <h2>Cost Planning</h2>
    <p>
      Belize is moderately priced by Caribbean standards—less expensive than the Cayman Islands or Bahamas, but more than mainland Latin America. Insurance costs are a significant budget item given the evacuation coverage necessity.
    </p>
    <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />
    <p>
      <strong>Total monthly budget</strong> varies significantly by location. Ambergris Caye retirement with comprehensive insurance typically runs $3,000-4,500 monthly. Inland Cayo District retirement might be achieved for $2,000-3,000. These figures include quality health insurance with evacuation coverage.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Insurance priority:</strong> Given Belize's healthcare limitations, skimping on insurance is not advisable. Budget $400-800 monthly for comprehensive international coverage. This is non-negotiable spending for safe retirement in Belize.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>QRP tax benefits:</strong> If you're importing a vehicle, household goods, or a boat, QRP's duty-free provisions can save thousands in import taxes. These one-time benefits partially offset the program's application costs.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Emergency fund:</strong> Maintain $10,000-15,000 in accessible funds—higher than recommendations for countries with better local healthcare. This covers potential evacuation deductibles, upfront costs before insurance reimbursement, and emergency travel expenses.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section id="faqs">
    <h2>Common Questions</h2>

    <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 mt-6">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is Belize safe for retirees with health conditions?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">It depends on the condition. Stable, well-managed conditions can be monitored locally with occasional specialist visits abroad. Conditions requiring frequent specialized care or emergency intervention may be challenging given evacuation requirements.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How quickly can I be evacuated in an emergency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">From Ambergris Caye to a Cancun hospital typically takes 3-5 hours including aircraft mobilization. From Belize City to Miami, 4-6 hours. Ground evacuation to Mexican border hospitals can be faster for some mainland locations. Insurance coordinates all logistics.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Can I use Chetumal or Merida for planned care?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes, many Belize retirees travel to Mexican border cities for specialist appointments, procedures, and even routine care that's better-equipped. International insurance typically covers this care. Chetumal is 3-4 hours from Belize City by car.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Is the $2,000/month QRP income requirement firm?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Yes, you must demonstrate $2,000 monthly from pension, Social Security, or retirement accounts. Investment income or savings drawdown can count if properly documented. The requirement is per individual—couples need $2,000 each, not combined.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Should I keep US doctors for ongoing care?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Many Belize retirees maintain relationships with US specialists and schedule annual check-ups during stateside visits. If you have ongoing conditions requiring specialist oversight, this hybrid approach works well with proper insurance coordination.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-neutral-200 p-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What about dental care in Belize?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-700">Basic dental care is available locally and inexpensive. Complex work is often done in Mexico or during US visits. Dental is typically excluded from health insurance, but out-of-pocket costs in Belize are reasonable for routine care.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Plan Your Belize Retirement?"
    description="Get personalized quotes from insurers with the evacuation coverage essential for safe retirement in Belize. Compare options for your age and health status."
    buttonText="Get Your Quotes"
